During the second half of the 19th century, the degentrification of the Place des Consuls—now known as Place Mohamed Ali—meant that elitist residences moved towards Rue Rosette, Moharrem Bey and further towards Ramleh. Filipo Pini Bey is said to have been the earliest promoter of the Quartier Tewfikieh (later known as Quartier Rosette or the Quartier Latin) in 1875. Pini subdivided its plots and developed some of its elite residences,including his own two Palazzinas in 1890, and that of Lutzzatto Pasha.

properties.Name_EN: Cordahi Complex and Sayed Darwish Theater
properties.Detials_En: The complex includes the Sayed Darwish Theater, owned by    G. Cordahi. It was designed by the French architect Georges Parcq in 1921 on the location where the old Zizinia Theater used to be. The surrounding two apartment buildings were designed by the same architect in 1928.  The Piazza contains a bronze statue of Nubar Pasha, Egypt’s Armenian Prime Minister, cast in Paris in 1903, sculpted by Puech.
The building was designed by the Greek architect P. Gripari, 1928, in the Neo-Renaissance style with an outstanding dome clearly seen from distance.

The villa was designed in the 1920s by the French architect V. Erlanger. The American Consulate bought the property from the successors of A. Bassili in 1960 and sold it to the Ministry of Culture in 1997. The project of transforming the building into the Alexandria National Museum started in 2001, and it was inaugurated in September 2003. The Italian architect Maurizzio de Paulo was in charge of the museum's interiors.

Originally belonging to the Aghion family, the Palazzina Aghion was built in 1887, when the Aghions had to move to the Rosetta Gate district after the British bombardment of Alexandria in 1882. It was designed by the Italian Architect A. Lasciac, following the eclectic Neo-Renaissance and mannerist style. The ownership of building transferred later to the Takla family. Nowadays the property is occupied by Al-Ahram newspaper.

In antiquity, the site of the Attarine Mosque is believed to have been occupied by a temple of Serapis, Alexandria’s most honored divinity. During the Christian period, the church of St. Athanasius replaced the temple, and later, with the Arab conquest, the church was transformed into a great square mosque. The present mosque, a renovation of the turn of the twentieth century, is a typical example of the Abbas Helmy II period, designed by the Ministry for Religious Endowments' technical office.
